### Rest Parameters

Rest parameters allow a function to accept an indefinite number of arguments as an array.

### Syntax

```typescript
function sum(...numbers: number[]): number {
  return numbers.reduce((total, n) => total + n, 0);
}

console.log(sum(1, 2, 3)); // 6
console.log(sum(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)); // 15
```

### Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|------------|
| Last parameter | Rest parameter must be the last parameter |
| One rest parameter | Only one rest parameter per function |
| Array type | The type must be an array type |

### Type Annotation

The rest parameter type must be an array:

```typescript
function join(separator: string, ...parts: string[]): string {
  return parts.join(separator);
}

function multiply(factor: number, ...values: number[]): number[] {
  return values.map((v) => v * factor);
}
```

### Tuple Rest Parameters

```typescript
function tuple<T extends any[]>(...args: T): T {
  return args;
}

let result = tuple("hello", 42, true);
// type: [string, number, boolean]
```

### Spread with Rest

```typescript
function sum(...numbers: number[]): number {
  return numbers.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
}

const nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
console.log(sum(...nums)); // Spread the array
```

> **Key Point:** Rest parameters collect multiple arguments into a single array parameter.

codeExample:
// Basic rest parameter
function logAll(...items: string[]): void {
  items.forEach((item) => console.log(item));
}
logAll("a", "b", "c");

// Mixed parameters with rest
function buildUrl(base: string, ...paths: string[]): string {
  return [base, ...paths].join("/");
}
console.log(buildUrl("api", "users", "123", "posts"));

// Generic tuple rest
function first<T extends any[]>(...args: T): T[0] {
  return args[0];
}
let firstValue = first(1, "two", true); // type: number
